                        "version": 0,
                        "content": "A client who is exhibiting psychotic behaviors is admitted to the psychiatric unit. In developing a plan of care, the nurse should identify which as the priority client problem?",
                        "subjectId": "ad5ab04c79144c0ea9b83385308c3b1d",
                        "difficultyIds": "80db17ea97ed8fdcd1b6b9666390fca1",
                        "difficulty": "考试范围-Applying 应用",
                        "textAnalysis": "Rationale:\nPsychosis is defined as a state in which a client's mental capacity to recognize reality and communicate and relate to others is impaired, thus interfering with the client's capacity to deal with life's demands. Disturbed thought processes generally indicate a state of increased anxiety in which hallucinations and delusions prevail. Although self-care and inadequate nutrition are important, the correct option is specific to the client and has priority. Lack of knowledge is not a priority at this time.\n\nClient Needs: Safe and Effective Care Environment\nClinical Judgment/Cognitive Skill(s): Generate Solutions\nCognitive Ability: Applying\nContent Area: Mental Health\nIntegrated Process: Nursing Process/Planning\nPriority Concepts: Psychosis, Safety\nStrategies: Strategic Words, Subject\n\nTest-Taking Strategy:\nNote the strategic word, priority. Focus on the subject, the client's diagnosis of psychosis. Recall that the client with psychotic behavior experiences disturbed thought processes, such as hallucinations and delusions, and that disturbed thought processes present a risk related to safety.\n",
                        "id": "4914bcda2165487e9ca38a3378b94985",
                        "mark": "0",
                        "collectionState": "0"
                    },
                    {
                        "optionList": [
                            {
